Discussion
his study demonstrates that  treatment has protective effects on burn-induced gut epithelial barrier dysfunction. ur data support the hypothesis that major burn injury induces -1± accumulation, which activates  and  gene transcription, leading to loss and redistribution of -1 and the subsequent increase in gut epithelial barrier permeability. ur results further demonstrate that  treatment inhibits -1± accumulation, resulting in reduced  and  levels, which in turn attenuate -1 degradation and redistribution, and thus protects against burn-induced gut epithelial barrier dysfunction.
he gastrointestinal tract is known to be a large pool of bacteria and endotoxin, and the intestinal epithelial barrier appears to play a critical role in preventing the translocation of luminal bacteria and endotoxin into systemic organs and tissues via lymphatic channel and blood stream. t has also been recognized that intestinal epithelial barrier dysfunction and increased intestinal permeability after thermal injury and may be the inciting incident that ultimately leads to  and  [1-3]. n this study, we used a rat model of 55%  scald injury in order to induce a significant changes in gut epithelial barrier function. n consistent with other studies [24,38,39], we noted that burn insults resulted in a significant mucosal damage and increased intestinal permeability both at 2 and 6 hours post-injury. 
t has been previously demonstrated that hemorrhagic shock is associated with acetylation imbalance of cardiac, lung, and liver histones, and that it can be restored by  inhibitors, including  [40,41]. n this study, we found that the levels of intestinal c-39 were reduced and administration of  significantly elevated c-39 levels. his indicates that intestinal acetylation balance is disturbed after burn injury and  treatment can restore acetylation homeostasis. urthermore, it has recently been shown that  treatment significantly attenuates ischemia-induced blood-brain barrier [34] and blood-spinal cord barrier disruption [29]. owever, the effects of  on burned-induced gut epithelial barrier disruption has not been studied. hus, we evaluated the effects of  on burned-induced gut epithelial barrier disruption using the hiuβ€™s grading system and intestinal permeability assay. n -treated animals, attenuation of burn-induced mucosal damage and intestinal permeability were only observed at 6 hours, but not at 2 hours post-burn. ince -1 is one of the tight junction proteins, which maintain the integrity of gut epithelial barrier, and recent studies have shown that burn insults cause changes in the -1 expression [18,24,37], therefore, we decided to investigate the effects of  on expression of intestinal -1. e found that burn insults resulted in a significant reduction in intestinal -1, which is in consistent with other studies, and that  treatment attenuated alterations of -1 at 6 hours, but not at 2 hours post-burn. his indicates that the protective effects of  on gut epithelial barrier dysfunction may be mediated through regulation of gene transcription and protein expression, processes which take time to cause a measurable effect.
