 and  are both downstream genes regulated by hypoxia-inducible factor-1 (-1), and increasing evidence suggests that -1 is a key regulator in paracelluar barrier function via regulating  and  expression [6,7].  recent study has shown that , also a histone deacetylase inhibitor, significantly attenuated the accumulation of -1± in macrophages cultured under hypoxic condition [33]. n the present study, we found that intestinal -1± was significantly increased both at 2 and 6 hours post-burn, and  treatment attenuated the accumulation of -1± at 2 and 6 hours post-burn. he effects of  on -1± occurred earlier than that on  and  expression, indicating that the protective effects of  on burn-induced intestinal epithelial barrier disruption may be mediated through its inhibitory effects on -1±. n order to confirm that the protective effects of  on gut epithelial barrier were mediated through repression of -1±, we used o. Cl2, a PHD inhibitor, to induce HIF-1Ξ± accumulation. We found that the protein levels of HIF-1Ξ±, MLCK and VEGF were significantly elevated while that of ZO-1 were decreased, and these changes could be repressed by VPA treatment. Furthermore, expression of MLCK and VEGF were significantly downregulated after HIF-1Ξ± siRNA transfection, accompanied by upregulation of ZO-1. These results indicate that VPA prevents gut epithelial barrier dysfunction by repressing HIF-1Ξ±.
It has been documented that HDACIs, including VPA, were able to repress HIF-1 function, however, the mechanism is not fully elucinated. Histone deacetylases compose a group of enzymes that can remove the acetyl groups from N-Ξµ-lysines of histones as well as many other non-histone proteins [47,48]. HIF-1Ξ± is easily detectable from the immunoprecipitates by using anti-acetyl-lysine antibodies and more recently, several studies showed direct detection of HIF-1Ξ± in immunoblotting with anti-acetyl-lysine antibodies [48]. It is proposed that acetylation of HIF-1Ξ± may induce degration of HIF-1Ξ± through promoting HIF-1Ξ± recognition and ubiquitination by VHL [48]. Therefore, one possibility is that HDACIs decrease the stability of HIF-1Ξ± through enhancing the acetylation of HIF-1Ξ± and/or other proteins involved in modulating the degradation of HIF-1Ξ±, thus accelerating the degradation of HIF-1Ξ± [48]. Further study is needed to identify the targets and define the specific acetylation sites responsible for HDACI-mediated HIF-1 repression. 
However, it should be noted that HIF-1 is a transcription factor which regulates a large number of hypoxia-induced genes other than VEGF and MLCK; and others have reported that HIF-1 and its downstream genes such as the multidrug resistance (MDR1) gene [49], intestinal trefoil factor [50], CD73 [50], adenosine A2B receptor [51] and mucin-3 [52] were implicated in the maintenance of barrier function during hypoxia. Different results between those mentioned above and ours may be due to the differences in models and the time points chosen to evaluate the barrier function. For example, they mainly focused on the role of HIF-1 in chronic hypoxia environment such as tumors and TNBS colitis, in which hypoxia develops slowly and the individual can adapt to hypoxia in a milder way. However, in our burn model, intestinal hypoxia develops quickly, and the rapid accumulation of HIF-1 resulted in a significant upregulation of VEGF and MLCK, which led to loss of ZO-1 and barrier dysfunction. Therefore, the role of HIF-1 in barrier function may be complicated, and drugs or other approaches targeting HIF-1 should be temporal specific.
In summary, VPA treatment protects against burn-induced gut epithelial barrier dysfunction by attenuating accumulation of HIF-1Ξ±, leading to a reduction in intestinal VEGF and MLCK expression and minimizing ZO-1 degradation.
